00:22:04.220 --> 00:22:08.080
necessary actually, in order to accurately try and ascribe

394
00:22:08.090 --> 00:22:12.000
these transcripts, ones that are coming perhaps from a different plane and look

395
00:22:12.100 --> 00:22:15.160
totally different than the cell that you're interested in.

396
00:22:15.579 --> 00:22:18.889
Those can be removed and/or you can redefine the

397
00:22:18.960 --> 00:22:21.440
boundaries for any cells that you're interested in.

398
00:22:22.340 --> 00:22:25.020
So there is a number of different tools, and if you are doing a lot of this spatial

399
00:22:25.040 --> 00:22:26.900
transcriptomics, I really employ you.

400
00:22:26.940 --> 00:22:30.040
These are mostly on BioRxiv, but they really clean up the data.

